  Industrial production converged with marketing and 
industrial 
economic efficiency improved remarkably. Sales of industry at 
above township level totaled 91.176 billion yuan, a 36.2 percent 
rise over 1992. The sales rate of manufactured goods reached 
96.6 percent, an increase of 1.7 percentage points. The 
composite efficiency index of independent accounting industrial 
enterprises at and above township levels was 105.64, an increase 
of 4.9 percentage points over 1992. 
  The ability to earn more foreign exchange from industrial 
exports was further enhanced. The number of enterprises with 
the right to independently export their goods increased from 53 
in 1992 to 80. The output value of exports by industrial 
enterprises at and above township level totaled 21.596 billion 
yuan, 6 billion yuan more than in the previous year. 
  The building trade maintained growth in production and 
vigorously opened up new markets. The output value of the 
building trade totaled 8.406 billion yuan, an increase of 28.3 
percent over 1992. Based on calculations of the output value of 
construction, overall labor productivity was 27,398 yuan, an 
increase of 48.5 percent over the previous year. The floor 
space of buildings under construction was 16.124 million square 
meters, with 6.475 million square meters completed during the 
year, an increase of 24.7 percent and 12.6 percent respectively 
over the previous year, both hitting an all-time high since the 
introduction of reform and opening up. 
  3. Investment in Fixed Assets 
  Fujian's urban and rural construction entered a new stage of 
rapid growth in 1993 and investment in fixed assets rose 
sharply. Investment in fixed assets totaled 33.8 billion yuan, 
an increase of 71.4 percent over 1992 or a real increase of 27.8 
percent after allowing for price hikes. Of this, investment by 
state-owned units was 23.5 billion yuan, up 89 percent; 
collective units, 3.3 billion yuan, up 44.9 percent; and the 
private sector, 7 billion yuan, up 39.4 percent. There were 
2,067 capital construction and technical transformation projects 
invested by state-owned units, 622 less than in 1992, accounting 
for 47 percent of the total number of construction projects. 
  Of investment in fixed assets by state-owned units, 
investment in capital construction totaled 12.3 billion yuan, up 
73 percent over 1992; technical transformation, 4.9 billion 
yuan, up 66.3 percent; commercial housing, 5.9 billion yuan, up 
176.9 percent; and other fields, 400 million yuan, up 94.9 
percent. Of investment in capital construction and technical 
transformation, investment by the center totaled 3.3 billion 
yuan, up 29.5 percent, and that by local units was 13.9 billion 
yuan, up 84.8 percent. 
  The investment setup changed somewhat. Of investment in 
fixed assets by state-owned units, investment in the industry 
was 300 million yuan, up 23 percent over 1992, and its 
proportion dropped from 1.7 percent to 1.1 percent; investment 
in secondary industry totaled 9.1 billion yuan, up 62.5 percent, 
and its overall share dropped from 45.3 percent to 38.8 percent; 
and investment in tertiary industry amounted to 14.1 billion 
yuan, up 115.3 percent, and its proportion increased from 53 
percent to 60.1 percent, of which investment in transportation, 
post, and telecommunications rose from 14.7 percent a year ago 
to 15.2 percent. 
  The year 1993 was a "year of infrastructure construction" 
for 
Fujian. In view of the central government's spirit of 
macroeconomic regulation and control, Fujian suspended a number 
of construction projects, curtailed the scope of some 
investment, and strengthened key construction projects and basic 
facilities. Key construction projects basically completed or in 
operation included the No. 1 generating unit of the Shuikou 
Hydropower Plant, the Nanyi Reservoir, the electrification of 
the Zhangzhou-Xiamen section of the Yingtan-Xiamen Railroad, the 
first-phase project of the Fuzhou New Port and a 7,500-ton 
capacity passenger port, the Fujian Oil Refinery, the Third Min 
Jiang Bridge, and a water plant in Fuzhou's western district. 
  Newly increased production capacity in 1993 through capital 
construction projects included: 510,000 tonnes of 
cargo-handling capacity, 220,000 kw of power generation 
capacity, 95.9 km of power lines, 600,000 volts of power 
transformer equipment, 150,000 tonnes of daily water supply, 158 
million cubic meters of water storage, 416,300 places for 
students in various types of schools, 54,400 telephone sets in 
urban areas, 5 bridges with a total length of 6,215 meters, 61 
km of highways, and the renovation of 209 km of highways. 
<H5>  4. Transportation, Posts, Telecommunications </H5>
  Fujian's "advance project" proceeded smoothly in 1993: The 
Yingtan-Xiamen railway was the first one to be electrified in 
eastern China, Fujian was the first province in China to attain 
programmed networks and digital transmission in post and 
telecommunications at and above county level, highway 
transportation was unprecedentedly busy, a trial flight at 
Wuyishan Airport was a success, and "bottlenecks" eased 
somewhat. The added value of transportation, post, and 
telecommunications was 5.115 billion yuan, an increase of 29.5 
percent over 1992. 


