  Post and telecommunications developed rapidly, with a volume 
of 2.422 billion yuan, up 64.9 percent over 1992. New 
functional services developed by leaps and bounds. By the end 
of 1993, the number of pager and mobile phone subscribers 
totaled 418,100 and 28,200, an increase of 190 percent and 159 
percent respectively over the previous year. The capacity of 
long-distance automatic switchboards was 105,700, up 178 
percent, and the switchboard capacity in urban and rural areas 
was 1.4763 million, up 84.5 percent. Of this, dialing 
telephones accounted for 93.1 percent. Long-distance telephone 
services and the number of urban and rural telephone subscribers 
increased by 83.1 percent and 75.4 percent respectively. 
  5. Domestic Trade and Market Prices 
  The domestic market for consumer goods continued to 
flourish. 
Retail sales of consumer goods in 1993 were 38.326 billion yuan, 
up 32.4 percent (or real growth of 16.3 percent allowing for 
price rises). Of this, sales at urban markets totaled 20.027 
billion yuan, up 40.1 percent, while sales in rural areas came 
to 18.299 billion yuan, up 25 percent. Despite an ample supply 
of consumer goods in the market, there was a great demand for 
high-grade goods. Transactions were brisk. Of sales of various 
consumer goods, growth and decreases were registered in the 
consumption of different food items: Grain, down 3.1 percent; 
edible oil, up 0.5 percent; pork, up 8.9 percent; and garments, 
up 27.5 percent. Sales of color television sets, washing 
machines, refrigerators, range hoods, air conditioners, and 
other durable consumer goods increased rapidly. There was a 
great demand for cosmetics, high-grade toys, and decorative 
articles. Other trades related to real estate rose 176.8 
percent over the previous year. 
  Retail sales of various types of commodities increased. 
Sales by the state sector rose 21.3 percent; by the collective 
sector, up 30.2 percent; and by the individual sector, up 44.2 
percent. A 29.3 percent rise was registered in transactions 
between farmers and nonagricultural persons. 
  Means of production markets continued to develop. Total 
purchases of the means of production by material supply and 
marketing departments in the whole province were 10.5 billion 
yuan, an increase of 58.2 percent over the previous year, while 
their sales amounted to 11 billion yuan, up 58.3 percent. Sales 
of rolled steel totaled 1.41 million tonnes, up 18.5 percent; 
caustic soda, 16,000 tonnes, up 20 percent; and trucks, 17,000, 
up 22.2 percent. The proportion of sales regulated by the market 
reached 97 percent, a rise of 5.6 percentage points over 1992. 
  Reform of the price system deepened further. The province 
lifted restrictions on prices of grain, edible oil, China-made 
cigarettes, iron ore, and manganese; readjusted prices for 
electricity, coal, salt for industrial purposes, cement, plastic 
sheeting for spring plowing, paper for press units, and embossed 
paper; strengthened management over real estate prices; and 
further rationalized prices. 
  The overall increase in market prices was rather high, in 
particular for service charges, investment in fixed assets, and 
energy and raw materials. 


