<H5>  6. Foreign Economy </H5>
  Foreign trade expanded further. According to foreign trade 
statistics, the volume of Fujian's imports and exports totaled 
$9.867 billion, up 49.9 percent over 1992. This included $5.825 
billion of exports, up 36.3 percent. Exports from the Xiamen 
Special Economic Zone accounted for 38.5 percent of the 
province's total, up 3.3 percentage points over 1992. 
  A new high tide appeared in foreign investment. In 1993, the 
province newly approved the establishment of 4,714 
foreign-funded enterprises, involving an agreed upon capital of 
$11.37 billion, an increase of 79 percent over the previous year 
and exceeding the sum of the past 14 years. The province 
actually used $2.87 billion of foreign capital, an increase of 
102 percent over 1992 and 92 percent of the sum of the past 14 
years. The average scale of foreign-funded enterprises reached 
$2.41 million, 18 percent higher than in the previous year. A 
total of 5,753 foreign-funded enterprises were completed and 
went into operation in 1993. 
  New headway was made in foreign economic and technological 
cooperation. Fujian contracted 3,172 foreign construction 
projects and labor service projects worth $680 million, an 
increase of 63.6 percent and 36.5 percent respectively over 
1992. The accomplished operation revenue reached $397 million, 
up 44.1 percent. By the end of 1993, the number of people 
working abroad totaled 29,800, 39 percent more than in the 
previous year. 
  International tourism developed rapidly. Fujian received 
193,000 foreign tourists, up 21.4 percent over 1992, and 668,400 
Chinese compatriots from Hong Kong, Macao, and Taiwan, up 5.6 
percent. Foreign exchange income from tourism amounted to $160 
million, up 11.1 percent over 1992. 
  7. Banking, Insurance, Taxation 
  In 1993, Fujian strengthened macroeconomic regulation and 
control, made strenuous efforts to muster and accommodate funds, 
readjusted the credit structure, and maintained stability in the 
banking order. At the end of 1993, savings deposits of various 
forms in the province's banks totaled 14.781 billion yuan. Of 
this, enterprise savings deposits increased by 5.024 billion 
yuan, and urban and rural savings deposits rose 6.712 billion 
yuan. Various forms of loans rose 17.155 billion yuan, of which 
circulating loans increased by 11.595 billion yuan and loans for 
fixed assets rose by 3.166 billion yuan. 
  Marked progress was made in insurance services. Premiums for 
various kinds of insurance in 1993 totaled 319.7 billion yuan, 
and income from insurance services amounted to 2.08 billion 
yuan, an increase of 59.9 percent over the previous year. 
Through deepening reform, changing operational mechanisms, 
optimizing the insurance structure, and improving management, 
the insurance departments attained relatively fair achievements. 
Some 25,000 enterprises and 1.51 million households 
participated in property insurance programs and 14.75 million 
persons in life insurance programs. A total of 390,000 motor 
vehicles were insured. Insurance companies took 358,000 
domestic claims and paid indemnity for 80,000 cases of property 
losses, 270,000 cases of loss of life, and 5,900 cases related 
to foreigners, which made contributions to stabilizing the 
economy and the people's livelihood. 
  New headway was made in taxation work. In 1993, the province 
received 9.197 billion yuan of industrial and commercial taxes, 
up 53.8 percent; 1.193 billion yuan of taxes from self-employed 
businessmen, up 45.1 percent; and 162 million yuan of income 
regulatory taxes from individuals, up 67 percent. 
<H5>  8. Science and Technology </H5>
  New progress was registered in science and technology. 
Fujian won 3 national spark awards, 172 provincial scientific 
and technological progress awards, 2 provincial scientific, 
technological, and foreign economic awards, and 13 provincial 
spark awards in 1993. Major scientific and technological 
achievements in 1993 included: comprehensive research on 
harnessing the lower reaches of the Min Jiang, a full set of 
technology for the construction of residential houses in towns, 
a study of diameter drilling and grouting capacity, molded foam 
EVA plastic, double wave-length continuous laser devices, and 
film machinery, which produced marked economic and social 
effects. 
  In 1993, the province carried out 178 national and 
provincial 
high-tech and torch schemes and developed 178 high-tech 
products, which added 2.3 billion yuan of efficiencies. The 
proportion of scientific and technological factors in the 
national economy increased remarkably. Fujian submitted 1,271 
patent applications to the China Patent Bureau in 1993, of which 
850 were approved. 
  The province enhanced the scientific and technological 
development capacity of enterprises. Investment in technical 
transformation totaled 3.353 billion yuan, an increase of 62.1 
percent over 1992. Large and medium-size industrial enterprises 
in Fujian had 151 special technological development offices, 
with 9,724 technicians. The ratio of special technological 
development offices and technicians for every 100 large and 
medium size enterprises increased by 0.2 percent and 1.7 percent 
respectively over 1992. Of 1,246 new products which went into 
operation, 138 reached world levels, 176 were national 
innovations, and 485 reached advanced national levels. 
  Import of advanced foreign technology were upgraded. The 
province approved imports of 64 advanced technologies in 1993, 
worth $120 million, or an increase of 107 percent over the same 
period in 1992. Both the scope and level of technological 
imports were upgraded, which accelerated the pace of technical 
transformation in old enterprises and increased the staying 
power of development. 
  New achievements were recorded in geological work. The 
province discovered 8 mines, made marked progress in surveying 
one mine, and verified reserves of 1.4884 million tonnes of 
gold, silver, and copper and 5.176 million tonnes of heavy metal 
ores. Geological departments submitted information on two 
bases, completed 4,932 square km of geological surveys on the 
scale of 1:50,000, and completed 74 million square km of 
gravimetric surveys on the scale of 1:200,000. Geohydrology, 
engineering geology, and environmental geology continued to play 
an important role in national economic construction. 
  Surveying work was further developed. The surveying 
departments used 144,000 working days to complete the drafting 
of 832 charts and the controlling of 959 charts, complete 1,782 
engineering survey maps and 413 relief maps, print 3,088 reams 
of maps, and complete 11,388 square km of aerial surveying. 
They also published 48 kinds of books. 
  In 1993, state-owned institutions in Fujian had 484,200 
professionals and technicians. There were 115 state-owned 
independent natural scientific and technological research 
institutes at and above prefectural and city levels, with a 
total of 8,708 staff members, of which 4,802 had senior titles. 
  The technology market remained active. A total of 4,220 
technological contracts were signed in 1993, with the volume 
reaching 187.58 million yuan, up 38.5 percent over 1992. The 
province held 16 technology trade fairs. A total of 6,083 
technology items were displayed and 344 contracts were signed, 
with the volume amounting to 226.68 million yuan. 
<H5>  9. Education and Culture </H5>
  Education developed vigorously. The 33 universities and 
colleges in Fujian enrolled 512 postgraduates, bringing the 
total number of postgraduates to 1,372. In the year, 394 
postgraduates completed their degrees. Institutions of higher 
learning enrolled 23,900 students and had a student body of 
64,100, and 16,500 students graduated from these institutions. 
  There were 107 technical schools in Fujian, with a student 
body of 74,700. Students enrolled by vocational schools 
increased by 30.8 percent, bringing the total number of students 
to 124,800. New headway was made in popularizing education. 
Junior middle schools had a student body of 1.1064 million. 
The ratio of children entering school was 99.6 percent, and for 
primary school pupils entering secondary schools it was 80.8 
percent. There were 974,900 children in nurseries and 
kindergartens. 
  Progress was made in the readjustment of adult education. 
Various forms of on-the-post training developed vigorously. In 
1993 adult universities enrolled 13,700 students. These 
universities had 30,000 students, of which 6,500 graduated. 
Adult technical schools had 48,800 students. A total of 
312,000 people escaped from illiteracy. 
  Cultural undertakings flourished. There were 90 artistic 
performance troupes, 80 cultural centers, 75 public libraries, 
64 museums and memorial halls, 33 radio stations, 36 radio 
transmission and relaying stations, and 15 television 
transmission and relay stations in Fujian in 1993. The province 
printed 458 million copies of newspapers and published 43.5 
million copies of various kinds of magazines and periodicals and 
170 million books. 
<H5>  10. Public Health and Sports </H5>
  Thanks to further improvement in medical conditions, public 
health developed continuously. By the end of 1993, there were 
45,232 various public health institutions, which included 1,190 
hospitals, 2,958 clinics, 12 sanatoriums, 99 epidemic prevention 
stations, 32 clinics for prevention of special diseases, 67 
maternal and child care centers, 13 medical research centers, 2 
medical colleges, and 23 medical schools. 
  By the end of 1993, hospitals had 63,500 beds and 90,400 
medical personnel, which included 38,300 doctors and 23,400 
nurses. 
  New successes were scored in sports. In major international 
games in 1993, Fujian's athletes won 30 gold medals, 14 silver 
medals, and 9 bronze medals. In national games, they won 27 
gold medals, 25 silver medals, and 13 bronze medals. An athlete 
broke two Asian records on two occasions. Mass sports 
activities were launched extensively. 
<H5>  11. Population and Living Standards </H5>
  Population growth was brought under control. According to a 
sample survey, the province's birth rate was 16.7 per thousand, 
the mortality rate was 5.6 per thousand, and the natural growth 
rate was 11.1 per thousand. By the end of 1993, the province's 
population stood at 31.5 million, 340,000 more than the end of 
1992. Marked results were achieved in family planning and the 
birth rate has dropped for three successive years. 
  Incomes of urban and rural inhabitants continued to 
increase. 
According to a sample survey, the annual per-capita income of 
urban residents for living expenses was 2,605 yuan, up 24.8 
percent from 1992 or a real increase of 6.8 percent allowing for 
price rises. The per-capita net income of rural residents was 
1,211 yuan, up 23 percent or a real growth of 7 percent allowing 
for price hikes. 
  The accelerated pace of reform in the field of labor further 
expanded the employment market. There were 275 employment 
agencies throughout the province by the end of 1993, and 128,200 
people were given jobs. The year-end unemployment rate was 
below 2 percent. Insurance coverage for the unemployed was 
further enhanced, with 11,400 units and 1.2868 million staff 
members participating in unemployment insurance. Relief funds 
were provided to 22,300 unemployed workers, and jobs were given 
to 10,600 workers who were on the waiting list. Progress was 
made in the contract employment system and exchanges of 
qualified personnel were active. By the end of 1993, the 
province sponsored around 100 different activities for exchanges 
of qualified personnel, invited more than 6,000 qualified 
personnel from other provinces, and helped with the placement of 
around 10,000 professionals and technicians in suitable 
positions. Comprehensive insurance for the elderly continued to 
expand. A total of 1.195 million staff and workers from 
state-owned enterprises joined the comprehensive insurance 
scheme, accounting for 93.7 percent of those eligible for the 
scheme. 
  By the end of 1993, staff and workers in Fujian numbered 
3.484 million, 76,000 more than in the previous year. Of the 
total, 2.243 million were employed by state-owned enterprises, 
773,000 by collective enterprises, and 468,000 by enterprises in 
other sectors. 
  The total wage bill of staff and workers in 1993 was 11.18 
billion yuan, up 21.8 percent over the previous year. The 
average wage of urban employees was 3,269 yuan per person, up 
17.7 percent or a real increase of 2 percent allowing for price 
hikes. 
  Urban and rural living conditions continued to improve. 
Housing space for urban and rural residents increased by 0.3 
square m and 2.74 square m respectively. 
  Social welfare continued to develop. There were 13,000 beds 
in various types of social welfare institutions, with 10,100 
occupants. Some 1.0543 million needy people received relief 
funds from the state. A total of 176 towns established rural 
social insurance network. An urban social insurance network 
also developed. There were 1,321 social service establishments 
in various districts. 
  Marked progress was made in environmental protection. By the 
end of 1993, there were 1,937 people working in the 
environmental protection sector, which encompassed 76 
environmental monitoring stations employing 778 workers. The 
number of projects against environmental pollution which were 
completed within the specified time amounted to 265, absorbing a 
total investment of 31.89 million yuan. A total of 83 
enterprises were closed, suspended from production, merged, 
switched to the production of other products, or moved because 
of pollution. The province established 156 soot-control zones, 
covering an area of 504 square km, and established 52 zones 
covering 57 square km, where noise pollution is controlled at 
specified levels. 
  Notes: 1. The figures in this communique do not include 
statistics on the Mazu Islands, which comprise Jinmen and 
Lianjiang counties. 
  2. The figures in this communique are preliminary 
statistics. Gross domestic product and value added by various 
sectors are at current prices, whereas growth rates are 
calculated at comparable prices. 

